title: Excitation functions of alpha- and He-3 particle induced nuclear reactions on highly enriched Sm-144 and Sm-147: comparative evaluation of production routes for Gd-147

Excitation functions of alpha- and He-3 particle
induced nuclear reactions on highly enriched Sm-144
and Sm-147: comparative evaluation of production
routes for Gd-147
, CV 28 cyclotron Juelich
enriched Sm-144 and Sm-147 in oxide form. The chemical
purity according to the supplier was >99.85% For Sm-144
and >99.44% For Sm-147.
isotopic composition in %
isotpe        material1           material2
samples were prepared by sedimentation 3-5 mg/cm2
on 12.5 micron Ti backings. The surface of the samples
were covered by 10 micron Al foil.
excitation function was measured via the
activation technique using stacked foil targets.
several stack, each containing 1O Sm samples were
irradiated for 1 hour at beam current of 300-500 Na
of 27.1 MeV and 35.8 MeV alpha and He-3 particle beam
respectively.
the beam current was determined via the monitor
reactions nat-Ti(He-3,x)V-48 and nat-Ti(a,x)Cr-51.
the energy degradation was calculated according to
williamson et al. (Tables of range and stopping power
of chemical elements for charged particles of energy
0.5 To 500 MeV, rapport CEA-R-3042, 1966).
nuclear data were taken from E. Browne, R.B.Firestone,
Table of radioactive isotopes, ed. V.S.Shirley,
Wiley, 1986, New York.

x4freetext: all the measured cross section data were corrected to
100% target enrichment.
the data for formation of Eu isotopes were corrected
for the decay of Gd parents.
data were taken from tables 3-5 of
Radiochimica Acta vol. 69,  Pp.209-213, 1995.
HW. Data units altered in subents 006, 007.
HW. Reaction sf6 modified in subent 006.-
BIB section upgrated
the uncertainty in the energy scale varied
from 0.3 MeV to 0.7 MeV for He-3 particles. A measured
cross section point below the treshold of 13.6 MeV for
the Sm-147(He3,x)Gd-147 indicates the large energy
scale error.
the overall uncertainty in each cross section
value was obtained by taking the square root of the sum
of the squares of the individual errors.
the typical errors were between 15-40%.
